How AROW Loads and Renders
The page source tells us exactly how it works:

Browser loads HTML
  → loads WebBuildMar27.loader.js (Unity's bootstrap)
  → loader fetches WebBuildMar27.wasm  (compiled C# game logic — binary)
  → loader fetches WebBuildMar27.data  (Unity assets — textures, models)
  → loader fetches WebBuildMar27.framework.js (Unity's JS runtime)
  → createUnityInstance() boots the app inside <canvas id="unity-canvas">
  → Unity renders frames to the canvas via WebGL
  → ALL text numbers you see are pixels painted to the canvas — not DOM elements


The values in your screenshot — 3,188 MPH, 127,703 MILES, 142,396 MILES — are not in the DOM at all. They’re just pixels on a <canvas>. That’s why normal scraping fails completely.

Extraction Strategies (Ranked by Value)
🥇 Strategy 1: Network Request Interception (Best option)
The Unity binary has to get the telemetry data from somewhere — it makes HTTP/WebSocket calls just like any other browser code. Playwright can intercept every network request the page makes before it reaches the server.

from playwright.async_api import async_playwright
import asyncio, json

async def intercept_arow():
    async with async_playwright() as p:
        browser = await p.chromium.launch()
        page = await browser.new_page()

        captured = []

        # Intercept ALL network requests the Unity app makes
        async def handle_request(request):
            url = request.url
            # Log anything that isn't the Unity binary assets themselves
            if not any(x in url for x in ['.wasm', '.data', '.js', 'fonts', 'png']):
                print(f"🔍 Interesting fetch: {url}")
                captured.append(url)

        async def handle_response(response):
            url = response.url
            if not any(x in url for x in ['.wasm', '.data', '.js', 'fonts', 'png']):
                try:
                    body = await response.text()
                    print(f"📦 Response from {url}:\n{body[:500]}")
                except:
                    pass

        page.on("request", handle_request)
        page.on("response", handle_response)

        await page.goto("https://www.nasa.gov/missions/artemis-ii/arow/")
        # Wait for Unity to fully boot and start pulling live data
        await asyncio.sleep(30)
        await browser.close()
        return captured

asyncio.run(intercept_arow())


What this reveals: If Unity is fetching from a NASA telemetry endpoint (a JSON feed, a WebSocket, a REST API), this catches it — URL, response body, everything. That endpoint would then be directly usable without needing AROW at all. This is the single most valuable thing to try.

